7. Endpoint Security

Endpoint Types

  • IT-centric devices
    • IP network-connected devices
    • Examples:
      • Servers/mainframes/storage, VMs
      • Network devices (routers, switches, Access Points, etc).
      • Client Computers, laptop/Desktop/Workstation
      • Point of Sale, Consoles
      • Mobile and Cellular devices, cellphones, tablets
      • IoT / Industrial Systems / Appliances
        • IP Enabled PLC, DCS, APC, RTU, etc.
        • Printers and Scanners, cameras, locks and physical access
  • Production-centric Devices
    • Non-IP Networks, often proprietary networking protocols
    • Examples:
      • Distributed control Systems (DCS)
      • Programmable Logic Controllers (PLC)
      • Advanced Programmable controllers (APC)
      • Remote Terminal Units (RTU)
      • Intelligent Electronic Devices (IED)
      • Wired/Wireless proprietary communications:
        • Local: Zigbee, DigiMesh, Matter, Multipoint, BT. and Bluetooth LE
        • Communications via Cat-M, NB-IoT (Low Energy proprietary Cellular Network), Virtual Carriers, Satellite, RF (Radio Frequency such as FM, AM, SW, etc.)

IT-Centric Endpoints

IT-Centric devices generally use standard and common communication protocols are used. TCP/IP is most common and is the standard for communications, therefore such endpoints are MAC/IP addressable. Such devices are easily discoverable on a network.
Devices that do run standard operating systems such as Unix/Linux/Windows are agent-friendly, so additional software can be installed to enable additional functionality and monitoring capabilities.
A few examples of vendors that provide hardware, software, and services are HP, IBM, Lenovo, Dell, Cisco, Microsoft, Google, Apple, etc.

Production-Centric Endpoints

Production-centric networks are usually found in businesses, enterprises, production, and manufacturing facilities. These are often heterogeneous and proprietary systems, that can have complex architectures. Due to the proprietary nature of such systems, these are incompatible with agent technologies and may contain hidden properties and features.
Some examples of vendors that provide such systems are Honeywell, Philips, ABB, Emerson, Yokogawa, Schneider, Siemens, etc.

Internal and External Attack and Threat Vectors

Attack vector is an industry term referring to methods used by threat sources (actors) to breach or infiltrate an information system.
Threat Vector is an industry term used to describe the method a threat source uses to gain initial access to a system.
The sources of threat and the methods they use to infiltrate systems are generally categorized as internal and external. Internal attacks can be more dangerous since the threat source has bypassed the edge defences and has potentially breached or bypassed some layers of security.
Examples of internal threat sources include current and former employees and staff, or any trusted person with access to internal systems, that may either cause a threat event due to error, omissions, or mistakes or due to malicious intent.
Backdoors External threat sources can also use social engineering such as phishing or other methods to gain access to information systems through an internal threat source.
External attack vectors usually are due to threat sources gaining access to a network or system using external communications over IP or non-IP-based networks.
Example Threats and Attack vectors:

  • LOLbins
    • Living Of The Land binaries, legitimate utilities and software that already exists in a system can also be used by threat sources as an attack vector
    • Monitoring tools will not consider these executables as malicious, making detection of malicious activity more challenging
  • Backdoors
    • Can exist due to
      • Non-malicious threats such as vendor default maintenance accounts and default passwords (Security misconfiguration, or intentionally left for convenience)
      • Legal requirements such as government access mandates and laws
      • Malicious intent, such as hacks or supply-chain attacks
  • Social Engineering
    • Internal or external threat source targets humans to manipulate the person with access to the system to take an action that may compromise security
  • Security misconfigurations
    • Can be anything from trivial to complex (oops... forgot to enable the firewall)
    • Most costly: incorrect access permissions in platforms such as Active Directory accounts or Cloud services (that could make the news!)
  • Malware (and Ransomware)
  • MITM (Man-In-The-Middle), or Adversary-in-the-middle
    • communication end-to-end is intercepted by a 3rd party
    • Can be simple eaves-dropping to extract information (confidentiality), or to intercept and change information presented to either side (Integrity)
  • DoS and DDoS
    • Denial of Service: any condition that affects the availability of a service to legitimate users
    • Distributed Denial of Service: a form of an IP attack where many sources (distributed sources) perform requests to flood the service so that legitimate access is affected (Availability)
  • Brute Force
    • Trying many iterations until credentials are found
    • Can be algorithmic to accelerate or to increase the probability of success
      • Accelerating brute forcing by using pre-calculated hash tables in memory instead of calculating values on the fly
      • Accelerating brute forcing using GPU or ASIC to try combinations faster
      • Use probability calculations to try more common values first (instead of trying all values sequentially)
      • Use quantum computers to try to factor primes for public key encryption (still not practical for large primes)
  • Session Hijacking
    • when applications' authenticated sessions or tokens are stolen
      • For example, single-sign-on (SSO) is used to authenticate a user to an application, and that authentication token is intercepted or exacted by an attacker to impersonate the user and bypass authentication.
  • Credential compromise
    • Weak passwords
      • brute-force
      • Password Spraying (trying out a list of known credentials, usually successful if passwords are reused by users)
    • Credential Theft
      • Using any method to obtain credentials, ranging from compromising a database of credentials to phishing and social engineering to tricking user into giving up their credentials
    • Replay attacks
      • pass-the-hash where the attacker only gets hold of the hash of the password, and can use the hash to authenticate, without having to break the hash to find the plain-text password
      • Token and session credentials (session hijacking)
      • Example: Car remote lock-unlock codes from key obs can be captured over the air, and replayed to the car to unlock the doors

Controls for Endpoints

There are many types of endpoints. The available option for securing an end-point varies. The variations and requirements are not universal as each organization has to determine its own risk profile and requirements. However, there are common controls that can fit many environments and situations.

Examples of some types of controls typical to most systems are:

  • OS and Software hardening
    • Removing/disabling unused functions, software and services to reduce the attack surface
    • Configuration Management, enabling and enforcing security settings (for example, local systems Firewall settings, limiting local user access privileges, etc.)
    • Installing timely updates and patches (patch management and automation)
    • Access control schemes, such as Least-privilege, Mandatory Access Control, Zero Trust
    • Data and Workload Isolation
  • Network and physical security
    • Controlling or limiting network access to the device (for example, using a NAT router, network firewall, network isolation, etc.)
    • Physical access to an endpoint may be controlled
      • Air-gapping (device or system is disconnected and physically isolated from other systems and networks)

For NIST's take on configuration management, see NIST SP 800-128: "Guide for Security-Focused Configuration Management of Information Systems"

For IT-centric systems that run standard and common OS, there are various options for security software and agents. Agent is a piece of software that is installed on an endpoint to enable functionality such as scanning and discovery, logging and auditing, monitoring, and configuration management. Some examples of agents include:

  • AV: signature-based detection of known viruses, malware, and other threats
  • EDR: behavioural and heuristic detection of anomalous behaviour on the local system, and responds by blocking access or terminating the offending process
  • XDR: Extends the behavioural detection to the network. Some advanced XDR agents can communicate with other agents (on other endpoints or a central command and control) in order to detect anomalous behaviours across the entire network and may have agency to respond by changing network configurations or firewall rules.
